african american arts winter lecture series cherise smith african american arts winter lecture series cherise smith displaying difference in adrian piper's mythic being this presentation examines the relationship of adrian piper's mythic being project to the discourse surrounding the politics of identity it explores the ways in which piper's use of her own body contributed to the creation of an empowered position from which artists could make art and identity cherise smith is assistant professor of art history at the university of texas at austin recently she was the recipient of the getty postdoctoral fellowship and ford foundation postdoctoral diversity fellowship her manuscript en acting others identity performance in works by eleanor antin nikki s lee adrian piper and anna deavere smith which historicizes the politics of identity in visual art of the united states from the last four decades is in production at duke university press she received her ph d from stanford university in 2005 more information date and time tuesday february 2 2010 5 00 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s location annenberg auditorium map audience faculty staff general public students category lectures readings sponsor department of art & art history contact 650 723 3404 risip stanford edu admission free and open to the public download add to personal calendar vcal record email event print use this permalink last modified january 29 2010
